I chose: - Amazon (AMZN) - Adobe (ADBE) - Microsoft (MSFT) - American Airlines (AAL) - Procter and Gamble (PG) - American Express (AXP) - Bank of America (BAC) - Apple (AAPL) - AT&T (T) - Caterpillar (CAT)

Exercise 1: Performance Analysis of Portfolios

Create (using four of the ten stocks) multiple portfolios using tq_portfolio(): * an equally weighted one, * a market-value weighted one, and * one where you create a trading strategy according to https://www.datacamp.com/community/tutorials/r-trading-tutorial - use the tools in the tidyquant package!! Trade your four stocks in a way that Portfolios weights (in sum) do never exceed +-1.

DO a performance analysis a la vignette("TQ05-performance-analysis-with-tidyquant").

For the first exercice, I selected the following stocks: - Amazon (AMZN) - Adobe (ADBE) - Microsoft (MSFT) - American Airlines (AAL) First, I want to get all returns for the stocks in one tibble and rename the column return

monthly_returns_stocks <- c("AMZN", "ADBE", "MSFT", "AAL") %>%
tq_get(get = "stock.prices", from = "2000-01-01", to = "2020-09-17") %>%
group_by(symbol)%>%
tq_transmute(adjusted, periodReturn, period = "monthly", col_rename =  "Ra")
monthly_returns_stocks

As a baseline, I will use the S&P500, because it includes the largest listed US-companies.

monthly_returns_baseline <- "^GSPC" %>%

Secondly, we want to create the market-value weighted one, using the follwing market values according to https://finance.yahoo.com/quote/: - Amazon: 1.55T - Adobe: 0.23016T - Microsoft: 1.57T - American Airlines: 0.00625T All companies together are worth 1.55+0.23016+1.57+0.00625 = 3.35641T. Therefore, we get the above follwing weights: AMZN 0.4618029 ADBE 0.06857327 MSFT 0.4677617 AAL 0.001862109

We save the market values as follows, using trillions due to the large numbers. We use the above mentioned values, divide them by the sum and control it - the sum of all weights has to equal 1.

marketcaps <- c(1.55,0.23016,1.57,0.00625) 
weights <- marketcaps/sum(marketcaps)
summary(weights)

weights

Finally, we are able to calculate the performance. We want to know each portfolio’s beta - the beta measures a security’s sensitivity to market risks. The lower, the better. The alpha describes the difference from expected and required return. The higher, the better.

multiple_portfolio %>%
  tq_performance(Ra = Ra, Rb = Rb, performance_fun = table.CAPM)

First, we create the mult_stocks, mult_Ra and mult_Sigma. We do this for the time period between 2000-01-01 to 2020-09-17.

mult_stocks <- tq_get(c("AMZN","ADBE","MSFT","AAL","PG","AXP","BAC","AAPL","T","CAT"),get = "stock.prices",from = "2000-01-01", to = "2020-09-17")
mult_Ra <- c("AMZN","ADBE","MSFT","AAL","PG","AXP","BAC","AAPL","T","CAT") %>% 
tq_get(get= "stock.prices", from ="2000-01-01", to = "2020-09-17") %>% 
group_by(symbol) %>% 
tq_transmute(select = adjusted, mutate_fun = periodReturn, period ="yearly",col_rename = "Mu")
mult_sigma <- c("AMZN","ADBE","MSFT","AAL","PG","AXP","BAC","AAPL","T","CAT") %>% 
tq_get(get= "stock.prices", from ="2000-01-01", to = "2020-09-17") %>% 
group_by(symbol) %>% 
tq_transmute(select = adjusted, mutate_fun = periodReturn, period ="yearly",col_rename = "Sigma")

Now, we stack them together.

mu_Ra <- aggregate(mult_Ra[3:3],list(mult_Ra$symbol),mean)
sigma_Ra <- aggregate(mult_sigma[3:3],list(mult_Ra$symbol),mean.stderr)
mult_sigma <- left_join(mu_Ra, sigma_Ra, by = "Group.1")

Now, we use ggplot to plot mu vs. sigma.

ggplot(mult_sigma,aes(x=Sigma, y=Mu,label=Group.1)) + geom_point(alpha =0.6) + coord_fixed() + scale_x_log10() + scale_y_log10() + geom_text(aes(label=Group.1),hjust=0, vjust=0)

# Now, we create a function in order to deliver the monthly returns since 2000
get_monthly_returns <- function(symbol){
  return <- tq_transmute(tq_get(symbol,
                                get = "stock.prices",
                                from = "2000-01-01",
                                to = "2019-08-31"),
                         select = adjusted,
                         col_rename = "monthly_return",
                         mutate_fun = periodReturn,
                         period = "monthly") %>%
    mutate(monthly_return = monthly_return * 100)
}

#rolling CAPM of our 4 stocks

In the next part, we want to create rolling CAPM of our4 stocks. We add the rolling CAPM to the Tibble ofr each Stock.

require(zoo)

add_rolling_capm <- function(joined_data_symbol){
  regr_fun <- function(data_xts) {
    lm(monthly_ret_rf ~ mktrf, data = as_tibble(data_xts)) %>% coef()
  }
  
  return <- joined_data_symbol %>%
    tq_mutate(mutate_fun = rollapply,
              width = 60, # 60 data (tibble) rows // 60 rows / 12 months = 5 years
              FUN = regr_fun,
              by.column = FALSE,
              col_rename = c("alpha", "beta"))
}
joined_data_amzn <- add_rolling_capm(joined_data_amzn)
joined_data_adbe <- add_rolling_capm(joined_data_adbe)
joined_data_msft <- add_rolling_capm(joined_data_msft)
joined_data_aal <- add_rolling_capm(joined_data_aal)

#plotting ALPHA

In this part, we want to create plots for alpha.

create_alpha_plot <- function(joined_data_symbol, title) {
  filter(joined_data_symbol, !is.na(alpha)) %>%
    ggplot(aes(x = date, y = alpha)) + 
        geom_line(size = 1, color = palette_light()[[1]]) + 
        geom_smooth() +
        labs(title = title, x = "") +
        theme_tq(base_size = 18)
}
create_alpha_plot(joined_data_amzn, "Amazon: 5 year rolling CAPM - alpha")

create_alpha_plot(joined_data_adbe, "Adobe: 5 year rolling CAPM - alpha")

create_alpha_plot(joined_data_msft, "Microsoft: 5 year rolling CAPM - alpha")

create_alpha_plot(joined_data_aal, "American Airlines: 5 year rolling CAPM - alpha")

#plotting beta

In this part, we want to create plots for beta.

create_beta_plot <- function(joined_data_symbol, title) {
  filter(joined_data_symbol, !is.na(alpha)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(x = date, y = beta))  + 
      geom_rect(xmin = as.numeric(ymd("2008-01-01")), 
                xmax = as.numeric(ymd("2009-03-01")), 
                ymin = 0, ymax = 10.0, 
                fill = palette_light()[[4]], alpha = 0.01) + 
      geom_line(size = 1, color = palette_light()[[1]]) +
      labs(title = title, x = "") + 
      theme_tq(base_size = 18)
}
create_beta_plot(joined_data_amzn, "Amazon: 5 year rolling CAPM - beta")

create_beta_plot(joined_data_adbe, "Adobe: 5 year rolling CAPM - beta")

create_beta_plot(joined_data_msft, "Microsoft: 5 year rolling CAPM - beta")

create_beta_plot(joined_data_aal, "American Airlines: 5 year rolling CAPM - beta")
